  "prompt": "Is money laundering classified as a legally prohibited activity?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is classified as a legally prohibited activity in many jurisdictions around the world. It involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (i.e., \"dirty money\") appear legal (i.e., \"clean\") by disguising the true origin of the funds. This practice is considered a serious crime because it enables criminals to profit from illegal activities while undermining the integrity of financial institutions and economies.\n\nIn China, for example, the **Anti-Money Laundering Law** explicitly prohibits money laundering and establishes strict regulations to combat it. Financial institutions and other relevant entities are required to monitor transactions, report suspicious activities, and comply with anti-money laundering (AML) measures. Violators can face severe penalties, including fines, imprisonment, or both.\n\nInternationally, organizations like the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) set global standards for combating money laundering, and many countries, including China, have implemented these standards into their domestic laws. Therefore, money laundering is universally recognized as a prohibited and punishable offense.",
